<subSubSection box="[199,1398,437,462]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,329,1182]" box="[199,1398,437,462]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,437,461]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is derived from the river La Vieja, the place where the species was collected at first.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,329,1182]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,472,497]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Description.</emphasis>
Male: Length of each forewing 
<quantity box="[708,845,473,498]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="6.9" metricValueMin="5.1" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="6.0" valueMax="6.9" valueMin="5.1">5.1–6.9 mm</quantity>
, wingspan 
<quantity box="[972,1096,473,497]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="13.0" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="12.0">12–14 mm</quantity>
. Head dark brown, setal warts light brown; antennae brown, each with scape and terminal flagellomeres pale brown; labial palpi and labrum pale grey; thorax chestnut brown, legs brown, spurs 2.4.3, spurs unmodified; fore- and hind wings fuscous, forewings in apical part of discoidal cell with oval patch of pure white hairs (
<figureCitation box="[866,968,581,606]" captionStart="FIGURES 16" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1122,1144]" captionTargetBox="[185,1404,200,1086]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[170,1418,195,1100]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 16A–16D. Trichoptera spp., photos of adults, dorsal view. 16A, Metrichia trisignata, male paratype; 16B, Xiphocentron laviejae spec. nov., male paratype 16C, Contulma spec., female; 16D, Helicopsyche merida, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606162/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Fig. 16B</figureCitation>
); anterolateral gland of sternum V behind oval thickening without process.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,329,1182]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[386,461,653,678]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1921,1943]" captionTargetBox="[198,1411,225,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[174,1411,193,1901]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Trichoptera spp., male genitalia. 7A–7C, Polycentropus joergenseni Ulmer 1909, scale = 0.5 mm: 7A, left lateral; 7B, ventral; 7C, dorsal.. 8A–8C, Xiphocentron laviejae spec. nov., scale = 0.3 mm: 8A, left lateral, with phallic apparatus in situ; 8B, ventral; 8C dorsal. 9A–9D, Smicridea colombosaucia spec. nov., scale = 0.25 mm: 9A,left lateral, with phallic apparatus in situ; 9B, phallic apparatus, left lateral with everted endotheca; 9C, dorsal; 9D, ventral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606154/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Figs 8</figureCitation>
A–8C): Tergum IX triangular in lateral view, anterior margin with deep U-shaped emargination in dorsal view, posterior margin slightly protruding and with small notch in middle; sternum IX long in lateral view, anterior margin with pair of slender, short apophyses, ventral margin slightly convex and dorsolateral margins relatively straight in lateral view, in ventral view sternum IX subrounded in appearance, posterior margin nearly straight in ventral view; preanal appendages long and sinuous, apices somewhat enlarged and rounded; inferior appendages each with broad, sub-quadrangular basal part abruptly separated from slender, clubbed, apical part, mesal side with series of small, black teeth; tergum X large with sclerotized dorsal ridge, membranous dorsoapically, ventral apex produced distad; phallic apparatus long and straight, reaching anterad to segment VI, flared at base and otherwise tubular to membranous, slightly widened tip with dorsal slit, middle section with spine-like structures on outer surface.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,329,1182]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1012,1037]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The species belongs to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authority="Banks 1941" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1941" box="[797,1107,1013,1038]" class="Insecta" family="Trichoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Antillotrichia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[797,948,1013,1037]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Antillotrichia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Banks, N." box="[964,1107,1013,1038]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" pagination="385 - 402" refId="ref7235" refString="Banks, N. (1941) New neuropteroid insects from the Antilles. Memorias de la Sociedad Cubana de Historia Natural, 15, 385 - 402, pls. 43 - 45." type="journal article" year="1941">Banks 1941</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which is characterized by unmodified tibial spurs, absence of black spines on the median sides of the inferior appendages, and a simple tergum X. According to the male genitalia, the new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Flint 1974 a" authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1974" box="[1024,1347,1085,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphocentronidae" genus="Xiphocentron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="surinamense">
<emphasis box="[1024,1202,1086,1109]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">X. surinamense</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Flint, O. S. Jr." box="[1214,1347,1085,1110]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 151" refId="ref7345" refString="Flint, O. S. Jr. (1974 a) The Trichoptera of Surinam. Studies of Neotropical caddisflies, XV. Studies on the Fauna of Suriname and other Guyanas, 14, 1 - 151, pls. 1 - 4." type="journal article" year="1974">Flint 1974a</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid 1982" authorityName="Schmid" authorityYear="1982" class="Insecta" family="Xiphocentronidae" genus="Xiphocentron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mnesteus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">X. mnesteus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Schmid, F." box="[260,411,1121,1146]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 127" refId="ref8329" refString="Schmid, F. (1982) La famille des Xiphocentronides (Trichoptera, Annulipalpia). Memoirs de la Societe entomologiques du Canada, 121, 1 - 127." type="journal article" year="1982">Schmid 1982</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the peculiar shape of the inferior appendages each with its subquadrangular basal part.
</paragraph>
